	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Revenue-sharing problems hit East Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												04 January 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>East African landlocked countries are reported in Tanzania’s <i>Guardian on Sunday </i>to ‘have raised a red flag against the proposed fully fledged regional single customs territory’, expressing concern that problems over the practicalities of customs revenue collection and distribution ‘could do more harm than good to their fragile economies’. Under the planned single customs territory (SCT), the partner states are to adopt a ‘destination model’ of clearance of goods, where assessment and collection of revenue are carried out at the first point of entry. This has the advantage that after payment of import duties (at Mombasa or Dar es Salaam), goods can circulate freely among the five member countries ‘in the same way as the goods produced in the region’.</p><p>It is argued that this will help to maximise the economic gains from the customs union. According to Hussein Kamote, Director of Policy and Research at the Confederation of Tanzania Industries (CTI), introducing a ‘fully fledged single customs territory would spur trade and investments’. Kenneth Bagamuhunda, Director of Customs at the EAC secretariat, maintains in addition that it will ‘crystallize the gains of integration characterized by minimal internal border controls and a more efficient institutional mechanism in clearing goods’.</p><p>However, Mr Kamote admitted that ‘most of our governments fear the EAC-SCT on grounds that the system may lead to loss of domestic revenues’ and loss of jobs, concluding that it was for CTI and policy makers ‘to clear their doubts’. This, others argue, will require major improvements in information sharing between the exporting and importing partner states of the EAC, so that accurate revenue sharing is possible and domestic revenue authorities can follow up on traders’ tax obligations. There are also concerns over losses in earnings to customs clearance agents in landlocked countries.</p><p>Such considerations are compounded by concerns, reported in <i>The Star </i>newspaper in Kenya, that the main regional seaports are already too congested. Kenyan Trade Minister Moses Wetangula has acknowledged that ‘congestion at the Mombasa port and various tariff and non-tariff barriers by Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA) are holding up’ EAC integration and regional trade. ‘I have been receiving complaints,’ the minister told a trade facilitation workshop, ‘from Uganda, Rwanda and DRC over delays at the port of Mombasa and more unwarranted charges imposed by KRA.’</p><p>These problems have already affected agricultural trade. There is a move by the KRA to require cash bonds from Ugandan importers for sugar&nbsp;and automobiles, as a result of accusations that some imports have been diverted onto the Kenyan market. This has seen sugar prices in Uganda shoot up and has further stimulated investment in sugar production in landlocked EAC countries (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/Kenyan-government-looking-to-broaden-revenue-receipts-for-sugar-farmers" target="_blank">Kenyan government looking to broaden revenue receipts for sugar farmers</a>’, 8 October 2012).</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Guardian on Sunday</i>, ‘Landlocked EAC countries fear single customs territory’, 9 October 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/10/09/landlocked-eac-countries-fear-single-customs-territory/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/10/09/landlocked-eac-countries-fear-single-cu...</a></p><p><i>The Star</i> (Nairobi), ‘Taxman is strangling EAC trade – minister’, 11 October 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/10/11/taxman-is-strangling-eac-trade-minister/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/10/11/taxman-is-strangling-eac-trade-minister/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Much of the debate over the advantages and disadvantages of regional integration focuses on the overall economic impact and its distributional effects. Advocates point to the greater output and competitiveness resulting from a larger market, while critics fear a loss of production and employment in the peripheral states and, in the absence of effective competition policy, the potential for predatory behaviour by dominant firms. But there is a set of more practical issues that need to be considered as well. Of particular importance is the question: where will import tax revenue be collected, and how will it be distributed within the region?</p><p>In an extreme case like EAC (where only two members have seaports) or SACU (where most goods enter via South Africa), there needs to be a mechanism that ensures that the import tax due on goods destined for Uganda, for example, actually ends up in Kampala. In addition, during the transition period of implementation where members may still have some differences in import/sales taxes, there is the reciprocal concern that goods supposedly destined for a national market with low taxes do not end up in a partner state with higher taxes.</p><p>The most direct way to avoid both problems is for goods to remain in bond until they reach the country of final destination and to pay import taxes at that point. However, this risks robbing the custom union of much of its anticipated economic gains – which arise precisely from the breaking down of such internal barriers. For the alternative ‘destination model’ to work, there is a need for three ingredients: adequate information systems to identify how much revenue is due to each partner state, an institutional infrastructure to deliver that revenue and, not least, trust that the collecting state will actually pass on the money that is due.</p><p>There is also a need for effective measures to prevent ‘rampant diversion of transit goods’, as is allegedly occurring in the sugar and automobile sectors in the EAC. In October 2012, a cash bond requirement was introduced by the KRA for sugar and automobiles destined for Uganda. This caused considerable controversy. The action of the KRA highlights the negative effects that ‘revenue leakage’ concerns can have on the free flow of goods within regional trade integration initiatives.</p>
		</div>
		
